Cars4U Project¶

By: Glen A Patterson

Date: 9-1-2022

Problem Statment:¶

Develop a pricing model that can effectively predict the price of used cars and can help the business find profitable strategies using differential pricing for their used cars.

Objective:¶

  • To explore and visualize the dataset using Univariate and Bivariate analysis.
  • Find key meaningful observations on the relationship between variables.
  • Build a linear regression model to predict the prices of used cars.
  • Generate a set of insights and recommendations that will help the business.

Data Dictionary:¶

  1. S.No.: Serial number
  2. Name: Name of the car which includes brand name and model name
  3. Location: Location in which the car is being sold or is available for purchase (cities)
  4. Year: Manufacturing year of the car
  5. Kilometers_driven: The total kilometers (a unit used to measure length or distance) driven in the car by the previous owner(s)
  6. Fuel_Type: The type of fuel used by the car (Petrol, Diesel, Electric, CNG, LPG)
  7. Transmission: The type of transmission used by the car (Automatic/Manual)
  8. Owner: Type of ownership
  9. Mileage: The standard mileage offered by the car company in kmpl or km/kg
  10. Engine: The displacement volume of the engine in CC
  11. Power: The maximum power of the engine in bhp
  12. Seats: The number of seats in the car
  13. New_Price: The price of a new car of the same model in INR Lakhs (1 Lakh INR = 100,000 INR)
  14. Price: The price of the used car in INR Lakhs

We need to now convert the string variables in "Mileage", "Engine", and "Power" to int and float types variables.¶

In [35]:
# we define a function to convert the strings to int or float type variables


def String_to_float(var):
    if isinstance(var, str):  # checking if the value is string or not
        spl = var.split(" ")  # splitting the value by space
        Mileage = float(spl[0])  # taking numeric part and convert to float variable
        return Mileage
    return np.nan  # will return NaN if value is not string


def String_to_int(var):
    if isinstance(var, str):  # checking if the value is string or not
        spl = var.split(" ")  # splitting the value by space
        Mileage = int(spl[0])  # taking numeric part and convert to int variable
        return Mileage
    return np.nan  # will return NaN if value is not string

In [43]:
# Convert Kilometers_Driven outlier 6500000 to Median average and Mileage zero to Mean average
for idx, row in df.iterrows():
    if df.loc[idx, "Kilometers_Driven"] == 6500000:
        df.loc[idx, "Kilometers_Driven"] = df["Kilometers_Driven"].median()
    if df.loc[idx, "Mileage"] == 0:
        df.loc[idx, "Mileage"] = df["Mileage"].mean()

Function for the Statistics about our models preformance¶

In [79]:
# function to compute different metrics to check performance of a regression model
def model_performance_regression(model, predictors, target):
    """
    Function to compute different metrics to check regression model performance

    model: regressor
    predictors: independent variables
    target: dependent variable
    """

    # predicting using the independent variables
    pred = model.predict(predictors)

    r2 = r2_score(target, pred)  # to compute R-squared
    mae = mean_absolute_error(target, pred)  # to compute MAE
    rmse = np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(target, pred))  # to compute RMSE

    # creating a dataframe of metrics
    df_perf = pd.DataFrame({"R-squared": r2, "MAE": mae, "RMSE": rmse}, index=[0],)

    return df_perf

  • We see that most of the columns have a very skewed distribution.
  • We will apply the log transformation to all but the Mileage and Year columns to deal with skewness in the data.
In [99]:
# creating a copy of the dataframe
df3 = df2.copy()

# Removing the Mileage column as it is almost normally distributed
dist_cols.remove("Mileage")
# Removing the Year column as log transformation will not help this distribution
dist_cols.remove("Year")
In [100]:
# Using log transforms to change all but Mileage column
for col in dist_cols:
    df3[col + "_log"] = np.log(df3[col] + 1)

# dropping the original columns
df3.drop(dist_cols, axis=1, inplace=True)

Observation on models performance:¶

  • $df$ dataset has a train and test $R^2$ value of 0.756 and 0.743, indicating that the model explains 75.6% and 74.3% of the total variation in the train and test sets respectively.
  • $df2$ dataset has a train and test $R^2$ value of 0.765 and 0.759, indicating that the model explains 76.5% and 75.9% of the total variation in the train and test sets respectively. This means that "Seats" treated as a category is a better model.
  • $df3$ dataset has a train and test $R^2$ value of 0.909 and 0.890, indicating that the model explains 90.9% and 89.0% of the total variation in the train and test sets respectively. This means that the log of Kilometers Drive, Engine, Power, New Price, and Price makes for the best model of the three.
  • We can see that $df3$ has only a $MAE$=0.1767 compared to $df$ with a $MAE$=3.027 mean error.
  • The overall performance is much better than the model we built in the previous session.

Conclusions:¶

  • We have been able to build a predictive model that can be used by Cars4U to predict the Pricing of used cars with an $R^2$ of 0.909 on the training set.

  • Cars4U can use this model to predict the used car pricing within a mean error of 0.176 on the test set.

  • The most important variables to find price is new car prices and engine size.

  • We improved our linear regression model performance by applying non-linear transformations to some of the attributes.

  • The train and test $R^2$ are 0.909 and 0.890, indicating that the model explains 91% and 89% of the total variation in the train and test sets respectively. Both scores are comparable.

  • RMSE values on the train and test sets are also comparable.

  • This shows that the model is not overfitting.

  • The overall performance is better than the model we built in the previous session, but linear regression would not be the best model.

  • To find Price of used cars: $Price=10^x$
